<h1>To John Hancock</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge 18th December 1775</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Captain Manly of the Lee armed Schooner took &amp; Sent into Beverly the sloop Betsey, A. Atkinson Master, She is an armed vessell, dispatchd by Lord Dunmore with Indian Corn, Potatoes &amp; Oats for the Army in Bostonthe paquetts of Letters found on board I have the honour to send you with this, by Captain James Chambers, they being of So Much importance that I do not think, it woud be prudent, to trust them by a Common express.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>As Lord Dunmores Schemes are fully Laid open in these Letters, I need not point out to the Congress, the necessity there is, of a vigorous exertion being adopted by them, to disposses his Lordship of the Strong hold he has got in Virginia, I do not mean to dictate, but I am Sure they will pardon me for giveing them freely my oppinion, which is, that the fate of America a good deal depends, on his being obliged to evacuate Norfolk this Winter, or notI have Kirkland well Secured, and think I will Send him to you for examinationby Most of the Letters relative to him, he is a dangerous fellowJohn Stewarts Letters and papers are of a very interesting natureGovernor Tonyns &amp; Many other Letters from Augustine Shew the weakness of the place, at the Same time, of what vast Consequence it woud be for us, to possess ourselves of it, &amp; the great quantity of Amunition Contained in the Fort;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> indeed these papers are of So great Consequence, that I think this, but little inferior to any prize, our famous Manly, has taken.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0574">[574]</span>
<p>We now work at our ease on Leechmores hill, on discovering our party there yesterday Morning, the ship which Lay opposite, began a Cannonade, to which Mount Horam added Some Shells,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> one of our men was wounded; we fired a few Shot from two eighteen pounders which are placed on Coble hill, and Soon obliged the Ship to Shift her StationShe now lyes in the Ferry wayand except a few shells from the Mount in Boston, (which do no execution), we have no interuption in prosecuting our works, which will, in a very Short time be Completed, when that is donewhen we have powder to Sport withI think, if the Congress resolve on the execution of the proposal made, relative to the town of Bostonit Can be done.</p>
<p>I have Sent a Letter in, this day to General How, of which, a Copy goes herewith<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0004-ptr">4</a>My reason for pointing out Brigadier Gen. Prescot as the object who is to Suffer Mr Allens fate, is that by Letters from General Schuyler, &amp; Copies of Letters from General Montgomery to Schuyler, I Am given to understand that Prescot is the Cause of Allens Sufferings<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0005-ptr">5</a>I thought it best to be decisive, on the occasion, as did the Generals whom I consulted thereon.</p>
<p>the returns for men inlisted Since my Last amount to about 1800 making in the whole 7140,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> the Militia that are come inboth from this Province &amp; New Hampshire are very fine looking men, &amp; go thro their duty with great alacrity, the dispatch made, both by the people in marching, &amp; by the Legislative powers in Complying with my requisition, has given me infinit Satisfaction.</p>
<p>Your Letter of the 8th instant with the explanatory resolve respecting my Calling forth the Militia &amp; minute men is Come to hand to which I shall pay all due attentionyou have removed all the difficulties which I Labourd under about the two Battalions of MarinesI Shall obey the orders of Congress in Looking out for proper officers to Comand that CorpsI make no doubt but when the money arrives to pay of the Arrears, &amp; the months advance, that it will be a great encouragement for the men to Inlist.</p>
<p>Inclosed is a Letter I Lately received from Mr James Lovell, his Case is truely pityable<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> I wish Some mode Coud be fallen upon to relieve him from the cruel Situation he is now inI am
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0575">[575]</span>
Sensible of the impropriety of exchangeing a Soldier for a Citizen, but there is Something So cruelly distressing in regard to this gentleman that I dare Say you will take it under your Consideration, I am with great respect Sir Your most Ob. H. St</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, in Stephen Moylans writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 152;

<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>;

copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span> item 169;

copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Morristown National Historical Park, Morristown, N.J. [[former abbreviation: NjMoHP]] ]">NjMoHP</span>;

<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.

Congress read this letter on 30 Dec. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span>,</span> 3:465).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>John Manley captured the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Betsey</span>, commanded by Midshipman John Atkinson, on 17 December. More than forty-five letters from Dunmore, Patrick Tonyn, John Stuart, and other British officials and officers at Norfolk, St. Augustine, and other places in the southern colonies were found on board the sloop. Many of the letters are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 151. James Chambers (17431805) of Pennsylvania was a captain in Col. William Thompsons regiment of riflemen. Chambers was promoted to lieutenant colonel of Thompsons regiment in March 1776, and a year later he became colonel of a Pennsylvania regiment. Chambers left the army in January 1781.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Moses Kirkland (d. 1787), a Loyalist from the Ninety Six district of South Carolina who fled to St. Augustine in September 1775, was a passenger aboard the sloop <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Betsey</span> on his way to Boston to present a scheme for subduing the southern colonies. GW sent Kirkland to Congress later this month for examination. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0560-0001" class="document">GW to Hancock, 25</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0579" class="document">31 Dec. 1775</a>. Kirkland escaped from the Philadelphia jail in May 1776 and subsequently served the British in the south as an Indian agent, a quartermaster, and a Loyalist militia commander. John Stuart was superintendent of Indian affairs for the southern district. Patrick Tonyn (17251804) served as governor of East Florida from 1774 to 1783.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The cannonade came from the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Scarborough</span> and the British emplacement on Mount Whoredom in Boston.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0529" class="document">GW to William Howe, this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0409" class="document">Schuyler to GW, 28 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>GW inserted the words making in the whole 7140 above the line in his writing. For GWs previous report on enlistments, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0487" class="document">GW to Hancock, 11 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0528-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>GW enclosed a copy of Lovells letter to him of 19 November. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0453" class="document">Lovell to GW, 6 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
